<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,548,679]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
While largely restricted to the Drysdale River system in the Kimberley, 
<taxonomicName box="[958,1206,548,572]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Melanotaeniidae" genus="Melanotaenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Atheriniformes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[958,1206,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Melanotaenia gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has also been found at one locality in the upper King George River (
<bibRefCitation author="Hutchins, J. B." box="[685,852,583,607]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="102 - 109" refId="ref18958" refString="Hutchins, J. B. (1977) The freshwater fish fauna of the Drysdale River National Park North Kimberley, Western Australia. In: Kabay, E. D. &amp; Burbidge, A. A. (Eds), A biological survey of the Drysdale River National Park North Kimberley, Western Australia in August, 1975. Wildlife Research Bulletin of Western Australia, 6, 102 - 109." type="journal article" year="1977">Hutchins 1977</bibRefCitation>
) and within one tributary of the Carson River (
<bibRefCitation author="Morgan, D. &amp; Cheinmora, D. &amp; Charles, A. &amp; Nulgit, P. &amp; Kimberley Language Resource Centre" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" refId="ref19400" refString="Morgan, D., Cheinmora, D., Charles, A., Nulgit, P. &amp; Kimberley Language Resource Centre. (2006) Fishes of the King Edward and Carson Rivers with their Belaa and Ngarinyin names. Murdoch University, Kimberley Language Resource Centre, Land &amp; Water Australia Project No. UMU 22. http: // www. cffr. murdoch. edu. au / reports / King _ Edward _ fishes _ final _ report. pdf" type="journal volume" year="2006">
Morgan 
<emphasis box="[199,249,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
, Morgan in press) (
<figureCitation box="[543,629,620,644]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="40.[151,250,1225,1248]" captionTargetBox="[262,1324,206,1200]" captionTargetId="figure-26@40.[256,1330,193,1204]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="FIGURE 20. Distribution of Melanotaenia gracilis in the Kimberley." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). It was particularly abundant at one site on the Carson River, with 265 individuals captured. It is unclear why it is not more widespread in the Carson River.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
